content.description:
Thong Wedgie uses the same anchors as

Highway 550 Revisited

and has a similar lay of the land. It has a thin move at the top.
content.protection: Quickdraws and gear for the anchors at the top.
content.location:
It is to the right of

Highway 550 Revisited

.

content.description:
At the right side of the slabby wall directly across from the restrooms, look for a bolt line just before the rock get overhung.  Climb up and right past a few bulges (crux at upper bulge) on good holds. Don't forget directionals for seconding climbers. From the top anchor, it is possible to top-rope the

San Juan Snake

, a harder (5.10?) overhung line to the right.
content.protection: 5 bolts to a 2-bolt anchor.
content.location: This is about 50 feet from the restrooms on the right side of the slabby wall.

content.description: This ascends a right-leaning crack that can be extended into Division Bell.
content.protection: Bolts.
content.location: It is in Rotary Park.

climbs.name: Sesame Street Extension
climbs.fa: Bolted by Chris Dobbins, 2009. FFA by L. Tyler

content.description:
Climb

Sesame Street

, and continue above on the slab that works into a right-facing corner. The hardest moves are at the bottom of the slab. Easier climbing in the corner above leads to some steep pulling to gain the anchors. Be careful what you grab, particularly at the top, because there's a lot of loose rock.
content.protection:
6 (?) bolts plus the bolts for

Sesame Street

.
content.location:
This is an extension that climbs the slab above the

Sesame Street

anchors.

content.description: This route climbs up plentiful small ledges up the lowest angle section of the slabby wall to a large ledge.  Great spot for kids, teaching leading, rappelling, etc.  Toprope as many variations as your imagination will allow.
content.protection: 3 bolts to a two-bolt anchor w/ lowering biners.
content.location: This is directly opposite the restrooms in the middle of the slabby lower wall.

content.description: This is a steep and juggy route that begins by climbing a small ramp that angles right above a spring coming out of the wall. The Ouray Rock Climbing guidebook stated Jason bolted this route on lead, with a self belay, hanging on with one hand and drilling with the other. It is a nice area in the shade.
content.protection: Quickdraws with gear for the top anchors.
content.location:
Start to the right of the lone tree on the right side of the wall, to the right of

Lap Route

.

content.description:
This route can be top roped from the same anchors as

Tepid Hummus

with quickdraws. Follow the bolt line with a nice and short haul. The climb is located directly in front of the large tree closest to the corner of the wall.
content.protection: 4 bolts to 2-bolt anchor or top rope.
content.location:
This is the first climb around the corner from

Tepid Hummus

with obvious bolts beneath the anchors.

content.description:
This has some tricky moves at times. Angle to the right at the top to shared anchors with the climb to the right,

Lap Route

. At the top, there's a bulge of rocks to make for an interesting finish.
content.protection: Quickdraws and gear for the anchors at the top.
content.location:
It starts only several feet to the right of

Thong Wedgie

.

content.description: Tackle the large bulge that has a nice undercling to get to the first bolt. Then find some well-placed handholds up to the crack within a right-facing bulge and some smaller holds to the finish. It is a short route but excellent to start in the 10c field.
content.protection: 4-5 bolts to 2 anchors.
content.location:
This is just to the right of

Jay's Route

. There are more climbs located to the right of this route, but I didn't get any good looks at them. Once again, they are in the guidebook by Jason Nelson and open for anyone else to add to this site.

content.description: Just like the others around it, Left Handed Blunt is a short climb that's great for beginners and learning. It has lots of easily worked ledges and holds. It can be messy with dirt and loose gravel, so be careful of what gets kicked around.
content.protection: 4 bolts to a two-bolt anchor.
content.location:
This one squeezes in between

Sesame Street

and

Tepid Hummus

directly across from the bathrooms.

content.description:
With mostly big jugs and big moves, this climb is harder than

RWRN

with which it shares anchors. Angle left at the top to do so. Attack the bulge at the finish.
content.protection: 6 boltsÂ with mussy hook anchors
content.location:
Start a couple of feet to the left of the leaning tree and several feet to the right of

Right Winged Red Neck

.

content.description:
Jason Nelson has a guide for the Ouray area climbs, the newest edition is available with updates. I attribute knowledge of this climb to his guidebook. The bolt line follows a route left of a slight bulge that is "

Pleasing the Masses

".
content.protection:
Bolts to the 2 anchors on

Tepid Hummus

.
content.location:
This is a few feet to the right of

San Juan Snake

and is also in front of the large tree.

content.description:
The

Ouray Climbing Guidebook

by Jason Nelson describes the climb: Climb up to a right-facing flake, then angle right through roofs above. You can also continue to the ledge at 105 feet for a longer 12a/b pitch. From these anchors, there are 3 more pitches above that is Hazy Shade of Winter.
content.protection: Quickdraws and gear for the anchors.
content.location: Start in the last little opening on the right side of the wall.

content.description:
P1. Climb a slab to an anchor.

P2. Continue up and to the right with big moves through the upper roof.

It is on p.118, #8, of

Climbs of the Million Dollar Highway

, 2018.
content.protection: Bolts with an anchor.
content.location: It is in Rotary Park.

climbs.name: Highway 550 Revisited
climbs.fa: Unknown, start finished by Jason Nelson and Matt Hepp

content.description:
This is a short route that angles right at the top to share the top anchors with

Thong Wedgie

, the climb to the right. Start only a few feet to the right of

Pleasing the Masses

.
content.protection: Bolts and gear for the anchors at the top.
content.location: Highway 550 Revisited starts to the left of the large, black colored section that goes all the way up.

content.description:
Hazy Shade of Winter is a 4 pitch sport route on the right side of the Rotary Rink Wall. The first pitch anchors are shared with

Industrial Measures

(11d).

Pitch 1: 12a.

Pitch 2: 12c, 100'.

Pitch 3: 12b.

Pitch 4: 12c.
content.protection: Quickdraws and a 60m rope. Pitch 2 is full 100' according to guidebook. While rapping, clipping back in will be necessary to avoid being stuck in hanging spaces.
content.location: It is on the far right end of the Rotary Rink Wall. This route, in addition to all the more difficult routes, are on the vertical/slightly overhanging wall.

content.description:
Climb a slab that gets steeper as you approach a bulge. Move right around the bulge (crux) and into a crack. Move through the roof to the anchors which are a few feet to the right of the anchors for

Dangling Participle

(5.9+).
content.protection: It is generously bolted with coldshuts at the top, 14 bolts total?
content.location: It is the 3rd bolted route right of the mound of dirt at the left side of the crag.

content.description: This is the middle of five bolt lines on the slabby wall, both in location and in difficulty. The crux is the lower well-protected bulge, then life gets easier. Be careful with one loose-looking block on the right 15 feet up!
content.protection: 4 bolts to a 2-bolt anchor.
content.location:
It is 10 feet right of the

Dipthong

.

content.description: Who says climbing can't be educational? Actually most climbers probably don't know what a dipthong is. (Is it something you might see on the Copacabana?) BONUS: try to come up with a new, independent dipthong for every successful ascent of this line!
content.protection: 5 bolts to a two-bolt anchor at a stance.
content.location: At the left side of the slabby wall, look for a bulge 40 feet up.  Start directly under the bulge.  Pull through a steep start then climb up and right of the bulge.  Climb on top of the bulge to the anchor.

content.description: "Circular Semantics" starts on the ledge, midway up the wall, on the west face of Rotary Park. It climbs past five bolts up the steep overhanging, orange and blue striped wall. It is best to either scramble up to the ledge via easy climbing, or climb one of the easier routes to a two bolt belay at the start of the route. It is better to belay from the ledge. Belaying from the ground causes many rope drag issues. The climbing is steep, powerful, and short. The anchor is equipped with rappel rings for an easy descent.
content.protection: 5 bolts. Quickdraws, rope.
content.location: Rotary Park, Ouray, CO. West Face.

content.description:
Who say's climbing can't be educational?  Don't use bad grammar or bad technique to climb this route with!

Left most route (to date) on the rink wall.
content.protection: 5 bolts and 1 medium cam to a two bolt anchor.
content.location:
Look for the same bulge as for the

Dipthong

.  Start left of the bulge and climb up a right-angling ramp.  Pull through the overhang left of the bulge, catch a breather, then do a cool high-step-rockover-stem (crux) up and left to the steep wall.  Punch it to the anchor.  Don't dangle too long!

content.description: As with most of the routes in this section of the wall, this is a short and enjoyable climb to begin lead climbing, learn rapelling, and lead belaying. The route is dirty like the others to its right.
content.protection: 3 bolts to two-bolt anchor.
content.location:
This route is located between

Dipthong

and

Sesame Street

. The bolts are easy to find.

content.description:
This is the first bolted route established on the same band of rock of the main walls, but far to the left. Â To the right of the climb, easy scrambling leads up several benches allowing TR access. The terrain steepens to vertical heading left. Â The route is right on the transition.

Pitch 1: clip the first bolt to secure the belay above the loose slope. Head straight up past 2 bolts on 5.5-5.6 terrain. The crux is surmounting the overhanging shelf, which is 5.7-5.8 depending on height. The crux could be bypassed at 5.6 or easier by heading right, possibly skipping the crux bolt if needed. 5.6 scrambling past one more bolt leads to the anchor. The route got its name from the two first bolts attempted at this station in the face of an oncoming lightning storm, which did not install successfully (chopping them is planned). Â First pitch was started by Mike with help from Aaron, Sam, and Paisley.

Pitch 2: This pitch is short to avoid rope drag and was completed in Aug 2020 by Mike & Logan. Â Stem up the hollow above the anchor and angle right and up onto a traversing wrap around the corner past 3 bolts to the anchor. Â Just above the start, a Claudius Simond piton was found, indicating prior ascents. Â Ironically, the first bolt installed here began spinning when we tried to change out the anchor hardware (chopping planned), requiring the current anchor to be established. Â This cemented the route's name.
content.protection: Pitch 1 = 5 bolts to a double rap anchor. Pitch 2 = 3 bolts to a double rap anchor.
content.location: Start to the left (north end) of the ice rink facing the cliff. Â Start uphill just behind the stored hockey goals and head up the loose hill angling left towards the biggest pine tree. Go up the small outcrop, finding the disintegrating green hardware store rope, and follow it to the first bolt.
